pullRequest.body:
We add `UniqueFactorizationMonoid.IsPrime.exists_mem_Prime_of_neq_bot`: if an integral domain is a `UniqueFactorizationMonoid`, then every nonzero prime ideal contains a prime element.

We plan to add the other implication (known as Kaplansky's criterion) in a future PR.

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion · obtain ⟨p, ha₅, ha₆⟩ := (hI₂.multiset_prod_mem_iff (factors a)).1 ha₄ ```

I have a five small nitpicks:

1. The doc string should be more human-friendly. I claim the main job of a doc string is to help a human recognise that the formal statement corresponds to what they expect in the informal literature. With that in mind I think we should use the phrase "unique factorization domain" instead.
2. The name should be `Ideal.IsPrime.exists_mem_prime_of_ne_bot` since the first hypothesis is `Ideal.IsPrime`, we camel case `Prime` to `prime`, and we almost always use `_ne_` rather than `_neq_`.
3. The proof can be simplified slightly by using `Ideal.mul_unit_mem_iff_mem` instead of `Ideal.IsPrime.mem_or_mem`.
4. [Subjective] Although it is not necessary, it is often helpful to provide types when using `obtain` to help the reader.
5. [Subjective] This is the only lemma in this file applying this theory to (ideals of) rings. I think it should be placed at the very end of the entire file. (I couldn't easily find a better home but I think it should not be mixed in with the general theory.)

All of this adds up to this suggestion to place the following at the end of the file:
```lean
open UniqueFactorizationMonoid in
/-- Every non-zero prime ideal in a unique factorization domain contains a prime element. -/
theorem Ideal.IsPrime.exists_mem_prime_of_ne_bot {R : Type*} [CommSemiring R] [IsDomain R]
    [UniqueFactorizationMonoid R] {I : Ideal R} (hI₂ : I.IsPrime) (hI : I ≠ ⊥) :
    ∃ x ∈ I, Prime x := by
  classical
  obtain ⟨a : R, ha₁ : a ∈ I, ha₂ : a ≠ 0⟩ := Submodule.exists_mem_ne_zero_of_ne_bot hI
  replace ha₁ : (factors a).prod ∈ I := by
    obtain ⟨u : Rˣ, hu : (factors a).prod * u = a⟩ := factors_prod ha₂
    rwa [← hu, mul_unit_mem_iff_mem _ u.isUnit] at ha₁
  obtain ⟨p : R, hp₁ : p ∈ factors a, hp₂ : p ∈ I⟩ :=
    (hI₂.multiset_prod_mem_iff_exists_mem <| factors a).1 ha₁
  exact ⟨p, hp₂, prime_of_factor p hp₁⟩
```
Thank you for your comments. They will be helpful for me in the future as well.
